Diagnostics are part of the compiler architecture, not a final pretty-printing step.

A build uses `StringTable` identity across config loading, frontend compilation, backend validation, output writing and diagnostic rendering.
Source locations store interned identity.
Renderers turn that identity into user-facing paths and names at the boundary.

## Core owners

- `src/compiler_frontend/compiler_messages/` owns typed diagnostics, labels, source locations, stable diagnostic descriptors, render-boundary aggregation and terminal/terse/dev-server renderers.
- `src/compiler_frontend/symbols/` owns canonical symbol identity used across diagnostics, imports and lowering.
- `src/compiler_frontend/symbols/interned_path.rs` owns interned source path identity.
- `src/compiler_frontend/paths/` owns path formatting and resolution helpers.

`CompilerDiagnostic` is the user-facing lane.
`CompilerError` is the internal and infrastructure lane.
Keep them separate.

## Diagnostic lanes

[table:
    [th:
        [: **Lane**]
        [: **Use it for**]
    ]

    [td:
        [: `CompilerDiagnostic`]
        [: Source, syntax, import, type, rule, borrow, config and deferred-feature failures that should be reported to the user.]
    ]

    [td:
        [: `CompilerError`]
        [: Internal compiler failures, filesystem failures, backend failures, dev-server failures and tooling infrastructure errors.]
    ]
]

User-facing diagnostics should carry structured facts.
Don't bake rendered prose into payloads when a reason enum, token, `TypeId`, symbol, path or source location can carry the real information.

`DiagnosticBag` is for stage-local accumulation.
`CompilerMessages` is for build/render boundaries.
That lets stages collect multiple useful diagnostics without pretending every validation helper needs to be an infrastructure failure.

## Source locations

`SourceLocation` stores interned path and scope identity.
It should not carry owned display paths.

Rendering and filesystem-adjacent code resolve interned paths through the active `StringTable`.
Boundary types such as `BuildResult` and failed `CompilerMessages` carry the string table so later output writing, terminal rendering and dev-server reporting can resolve paths consistently.

This makes diagnostics durable across the whole build.
A diagnostic produced during config loading can still render accurately after backend validation fails.
A module warning can survive project assembly without losing its path context.

## Type diagnostics

Type diagnostics should carry semantic `TypeId`s and render through `DiagnosticRenderContext` when the relevant module `TypeEnvironment` is available.

Do this:

- carry canonical `TypeId`s
- carry context enums and structured reasons
- resolve source-level names at the render boundary

Don't do this:

- clone `DataType` values for semantic diagnostics
- store formatted type names early
- compare types by syntax spelling

The active `TypeEnvironment` decides type identity.
The renderer decides how to explain that identity.

## StringTable fork and merge rules

Parallel work can fork string tables only when deltas are merged and remapped in deterministic order before later stages consume tokens, headers, diagnostics or type-rendering context.

Directory project compilation creates one shared string-table fork source for the module batch.
Each module compiles with a local delta over that immutable base.
The build system then merges local suffixes in deterministic entry-path order and remaps module payloads, diagnostics and render type environments only when the returned remap is non-identity.

Inside a module, source files can be prepared in parallel.
Each file tokenizes and header-parses against a local string-table fork.
The module frontend merges file deltas back into the module table in deterministic input order and remaps tokens, headers, warnings and diagnostics before module-wide header aggregation, dependency sorting and AST construction.

Full `StringTable` cloning and full-table merging remain available for true independent table boundaries.
They should not be used for ordinary parallel module compilation.

## Style directives

Project builders can register style directives through `frontend_style_directives`.

- Frontend-owned directives are always available.
- Builder directives cannot override frontend-owned names.
- Tokenizer and template parsing use the same merged registry.
- Unknown directives are rejected strictly.

Directive syntax belongs to the language/template docs.
The compiler-design concern is ownership: the registry is merged before tokenizer/template parsing, and every consumer sees the same directive availability.

## Deferred and outside-scope diagnostics

Design-scope and deferred-feature diagnostics should be centralised through typed `CompilerDiagnostic` constructors.

Deferred features and outside-design-scope rejections must stay distinct.
A deferred feature says, "this fits the design, but not this surface yet".
An outside-scope feature says, "this would change the language philosophy".

That distinction matters for implementation work.
Deferred features can become roadmap items.
Outside-scope features need an explicit design change before code tries to support them.

